>dear Dr Bougault, I read this very interesting discussion about
>the micro entropy. First comments to the paper PRL 83,p3150 by Melby
>et al.:
>I fully agree with you that fig. 2 shows nicely the backbending
>of T_micro as was proposed since 1982. In my recent paper I discuss
>its consequences for our fundamental understanding of thermodynamics
>of "small" systems, on phase transitions and in the Second Law of
>thermodynamics.
>->http://arXiv.org/abs/cond-mat/?9911257
>
>On my earlier papers on nuclear level density and caloric curves, I
>was, however, mainly concerned with the higher excitation energies in
>the region of nuclear fragmentation i.e.  E>3*A MeV. Here the level
>density is certainly more smooth and the discretenes is not so much a
>problem. Therefore, I paid little attention to define rigorously the
>differentiation procedure like 1/T=dS/dE in the case of discrete
>levels.
>
>The paper nucl-exp/9911011 by Guttormsen is a beautiful work that
>illustrates all the main points. Fig.3 shows the effect of the
>smoothing. Certainly, the gaps and negative temperatures are
>important - however, from the thermodynamic point of view -- exotic
>specialities of the micro entropy. These indicate an instability
>of this system if it would be imposed to heat bath. But this is
>anyhow not possible. Experimentally, this is only seen for 162Dy
>at E*~0.5 MeV. At higher excitation other states than the pure
>eigen states of the simplfied pairing model wash these regions
>of negative T out. This paper is exciting and shows clearly the
>pecularities of small systems thermodynamics. Still, I think,
>the Second Law is fulfilled in spite of neg.T.
>
>You write that in the work with Michaela d'Agostino you see only one
>region of negative spec.heat (Though certainly pos.T). This is similar
>to my finding for the fragmentation of large nuclei.  Here are so many
>decay channels open, that the backbending is not anymore due to a
>single channel but characterizes more a topological change of several
>decay modes.
>
>
>
>Dieter Gross
